g of the history of modern European verse, the troubadours were the prime poets and composers of the twelfth and thirteenth centuries in the South of France. No study of medieval literature is complete without an examination of the courtly love which is celebrated in the elaborately rhymed stanzas of troubadour verse, creations whose words and melodies were imitated by poets and musicians all over medieval Europe.The words of about 2,500 troubadour songs have survived, along with 250 melodies, and all have come under intense scholarly scrutiny. This Handbook brings together the fruits of this scrutiny, giving teachers and students an overview of the fundamental issues in troubadour scholarship. All "ations are given in the original Old Occitan and in English. The editors provide a list of troubadour editions and an index, and each chapter includes a list of additional readings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aProvençal poetryxCriticism, TextualvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aProvençal poetryxHistory and criticismvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aTroubadoursvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  a12th century european art history.  a13th century european art history.  acenter for medieval and renaissance studies ucla.  acomposers.  acourtly love.  aeuropean literature.  afemale troubadours.  afrance.  afrench troubadours.  aiberian peninsula.  aimagery.  aitalian troubadours.  aitaly.  amedieval literary criticism.  amedieval literature.  amedieval occitan studies.  aminnesingers.  amodern european verse.  amusic.  anon lyric text.  apoets.  atopoi.  atroubadour poetry.  atroubadour studies.  atroubadour verse.  atroubadours.  aversification.  avocabulary.1 aAkehurst, F. R P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab